461,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-24 00:41:18+00:00,7568434,paulfitz/daff,1596071,jheeffer,,,197309348,269060555,"Looks good! So if I get it correctly, the eol of the first line of one of the two files will be used? I guess that's a good enough solution, if it's clear which file the eol's are used from (if they conflict). No need to do it on a per line basis most likely.",{},,User,False
463,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-17 19:06:19+00:00,19384977,peplin/pygatt,2152464,dcliftreaves,,,177527399,247798230,"I don't think the 1 second approach is a great idea. 
My infinite loop approach may not be great but you could put a for loop there with a 0.25 wait and have it run enough times to retry for 5 seconds or so.

The problem with what you have done is that the serial port re-appearing is heavily dependent on drivers and CPU load and your OS in general. I don't think 1 second will work for everyone all the time. Having a ~5 second timeout is reasonable though. (Or you can tie it to the timeout passed in.)

The issue with missing the system_boot event is due to timing. If you can't catch the serial port and open it before the device decides to simply output that message then you miss it. So it is essentially a race. I was trying to build it so that it would catch it but I certainly can understand that is a bad idea. It is very likely that on some systems you will never be able to catch it. It is also possible that older versions of the FW might not even emit it.

I did actually know about the tty enumeration issue. This is very common and an OS/driver issue essentially. What happens is that the timeout for waiting to find out if a device has disappeared is longer than the wait time to create a device is a new one has appeared. The OS (like in many other scenarios) just increments a counter because it would rather not have collisions then assume something is the same thing. I don't know of a great work around for this issue. My computer appears to be fast enough to not run into the problem. But, I have a windows system I run this on that has had this issue many times when I was unplugging and re-plugging the device physically. I had to implement a system where I counted to 10 before plugging it back in. That was one of the things that made me what to create a software solution for this.

",{},,User,False
