782,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-20 11:33:01+00:00,54787116,guyzmo/git-repo,254441,guyzmo,,,200620138,274051717,"I've had a little thought about this, and here's how I think `git XXX request` shall behave:

```
git XXX request create ""title"" [--message=""message""]
```

* create a new request of the current branch on the current repository's parent fork's main branch, as registered on the service.
* If current repository is not a fork, use it instead.
* If the branch hasn't been pushed (yet), throw an error.

```
git XXX request create <branch> ""title"" [--message=""message""]
```

* create a new request of the given branch `<branch>` on the current repository's parent fork's main branch, as registered on the service.
* If current repository is not a fork, use it instead.
* If the branch hasn't been pushed (yet), throw an error.

```
git XXX request create <branch> <onto> ""title"" [--message=""message""]
```

* create a new request of the given branch `<branch>` on the current repository's parent fork's given `<onto>` branch, as registered on the service.
* If current repository is not a fork, use it instead.
* If the branch hasn't been pushed (yet), throw an error.

```
git XXX request <user/repo> create [<branch> [<onto>]]  ""title"" [--message=""message""]
```

* same as above, but instead of using current repository's parent fork (or current repository as fallback), use given repository `<user/repo>`.",{},,User,False
