1461,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-25 15:09:17+00:00,122181085,bashtage/randomgen,5585221,bashtage,,,301388331,392088390,"Anytime you generate a random value you are going to modify the state in one way or another. 

Under the hoot when you call

```
rng.next_uint64(rng.state)
```

the random number generator is called (in C) taking the state as an argument.  The C code modifies the state so that rng.state is changed in place. 


In terms of using the distributions, a minimal example is something like 

```
cimport cython
from cpython.pycapsule cimport PyCapsule_GetPointer
from randomgen.common cimport brng_t
from randomgen.distributions cimport random_gauss_zig

def myf(r):
    cdef brng_t *rng
    cdef double i
    cdef const char *name = 'BasicRNG'
    rng = <brng_t *> PyCapsule_GetPointer(r.capsule, name)
    i = random_gauss_zig(rng)

    return i
```

Which will return a random double generated using the ZIggurat method. All of the function in randomgen.distributions.pxd just take a `brng*` as their only argument (except one, which takes a complex struct that is used internally to the function). 
",{},OWNER,User,False
