1832,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-20 12:26:35+00:00,96678616,miyuchina/mistletoe,14964777,miyuchina,,,352086063,414299215,"Hi there!

According to [CommonMark](https://spec.commonmark.org/0.28/#loose):

> A list is loose if any of its constituent list items are separated by blank lines, or if any of its constituent list items directly contain two block-level elements with a blank line between them. Otherwise a list is tight. (The difference in HTML output is that paragraphs in a loose list are wrapped in `<p>` tags, while paragraphs in a tight list are not.)

So:

```markdown
- a
- b

- c
```

... will be rendered to:

```html
<ul>
<li>
<p>a</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>b</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>c</p>
</li>
</ul>
```

And:

```markdown
- a
- b
- c
```

... will be rendered to:

```html
<ul>
<li>a</li>
<li>b</li>
<li>c</li>
</ul>
```

Can you attach the wrong example you're seeing?",{},OWNER,User,False
