5330,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-25 12:14:10+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,64938,ants,1564818,zalando,221266394,297011019,"I haven't seen any examples of this kind of overlap in the wild, but in theory it's possible. We could invent hacks to get around this, either a magically named key in the nested structure for the scalar value, or fall back to dotted representation when the prefix is already taken by a scalar value. I kind of like the latter variant. The complexity will all be compartmentalized to the UI side, the conversion done when converting to/from JSON. When loading postgresql.parameters we check for names with dots and if they exist and the prefix key does not, we convert it to a dict. When storing back it's just a matter of flattening any dicts out to dotted representation.

    # prettify({""work_mem.bla"": ""foo""})
    work_mem:
      bla: foo

    # prettify({""work_mem.bla"": ""foo"", ""work_mem"": ""4MB""})
    work_mem: 4MB
    work_mem.bla: foo
",{},,User,False
