5507,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-16 15:35:31+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,12146674,zzsfornlp,2374376,clab,253751887,329975747,"Thanks for the comments. I see that memory issue is not the most important one and including inplace operations inevitably brings maybe-hard-to-control complexities. And with dynamic nets, we can only rely on the users themselves to decide whether to do the inplace operations. Those indeed makes these inplace operations not that appealing.

I still think using methods to save memories could be helpful, especially there are situations when we might need to save some. In fact, I experiment using ``inplace-tanh'' in the attention part of att-seq2seq, and it seems to be able to save at least up to 500MB memories.

Although using inplace operations is the choices for users, but the system can also check whether the operations are legal (whether they are using rewritten/staled values) (Currently this is done when building the graph). Thus the risks should be controlled and checked by the system (throwing error when illegal things happen), currently I'm doing this in `set_inplace_for_new_node`.

Yes, I agree that complexing the internal codes might not be a good idea, and it is only until recently (sorry about this) that I find this bug, which could be really dangerous and break down the gradient calculating (silently). And maybe this really opens too much to the users?  But I cannot think of other ways to do that without slightly changing the internals, I don't know whether this is done appropriately.  Thanks for the review and help.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
