5698,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-06 08:03:34+00:00,11031844,uqfoundation/dill,321534,mmckerns,2855931,uqfoundation,55144138,277609294,"Note that `pickle` does the following, to avoid recursion:
```
        if id(obj) in self.memo:
            # If the object is already in the memo, this means it is
            # recursive. In this case, throw away everything we put on the
            # stack, and fetch the object back from the memo.
            write(POP_MARK + self.get(self.memo[id(obj)][0]))
            return
```
Maybe something like this is a better solution... as it's pretty hard to get anything from a cell except what the `cell_contents` are.",{},,User,False
5699,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-29 14:33:21+00:00,11031844,uqfoundation/dill,3201565,kirillmakhonin,2855931,uqfoundation,314105032,401372775,"This is because numpy (and pandas) override magic methods that uses for comparing. For example `__bool__` magic method in pandas. As a workaround you may patch this magic method (`pandas....DataFrame.__bool__ = lambda x: True`) but I think this is very bad way. I think, we can replace `==` equation with `is` in dill.detect:214",{},NONE,User,False
