6223,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-28 20:19:32+00:00,47576910,googlei18n/fontmake,1923747,moyogo,5503833,googlei18n,185962205,257018387,"@marekjez86 it is recommended to use ""production names"" which meet the requirements defined in https://github.com/adobe-type-tools/agl-specification and https://github.com/adobe-type-tools/agl-aglfn. The ""production names"" in the final font must only use characters allowed by the Postscript specifications. These are also called PostScript names.

The term ""Production names"" can be confusing but it’s Glyphs.app terminology. See https://www.glyphsapp.com/content/1-get-started/2-manuals/1-handbook-glyphs-2-0/Glyphs-Handbook-2.3.pdf section 6.6.1 Glyph Info Database
> Glyphs contains a glyph info database. For each glyph, the
> database defines:
> • the human-readable (or ‘nice’) glyph name,
> • the production names, i.e., the name as required for the
> exported installable font file
> [...]

Once one know that, fontmake’s help already makes it clear that `--production-names` renames the glyphs and sort of implies `--no-production-names` doesn’t.
```
  --production-names    Rename glyphs with production names if available
                        otherwise use uninames.
  --no-production-names
```

It might be good to be explicit about what `--no-production` does and clarify that there is a third option and what it does. Would that be enough?
If that also helps one could find better names for these options.",{},,User,False
