6326,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-16 20:02:28+00:00,23788348,swisscom/cleanerversion,4340785,boydjohnson,5754111,swisscom,87226878,112551871,"In Python 2 you can use the \__unicode\__ method and prepend u'' to everything. Check out [django docs](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.8/topics/python3/#string-handling) for reading on unicode handling in Python 2 and 3. You can use a class decorator python_2_unicode_compatible to make the \__str\__ into a \__unicode\__ in Python 2 and do nothing in Python 3, to make the code compatible with Python 2 and 3. I haven't gotten the decorator to work yet on the versions_tests code, but I did get it to work correctly in Python 2 by just renaming \__str\__ as \__unicode\__",{},,User,False
