6540,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-07 16:27:26+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,38393,msarahan,6392739,conda,115092426,154720739,"> Where does the ""single package"" fit in here

I misspoke.  It is a single recipe that generates multiple packages.  I tried this morning to change it to 3 separate recipes, each named msvc_runtime, but with different versions.  I tried this two different ways:

  1. Individual folders, msvc_runtime-9.0.???? and so on.  Our build system gets confused by multiple packages named msvc_runtime.  Needs work.
  2. Adding selectors to version field of package metadata in meta.yaml, in single recipe.  Selectors don't seem to be supported in that field, unfortunately.

I am leaving it as is for the time being, but noting that this issue is something that needs urgent work in our build system, and potentially also with conda-build to add support for selectors everywhere in meta.yaml.  Templating with jinja2 might be a better way to do this, but the build system does not cache generated jinja2 output, so the metadata to populate the index currently has to come from static, non-templated files.

> In fact, I believe that any compiled Python module that #includes numpy headers needs at least three features: the compiler version, the Python version, and the numpy version.

I agree with you in principal, but the compiler version is somewhat implicit in the Python version.  We are not going to support using compilers other than the ones officially used to build Python.  Thus, Python2.7 specifies MSVC 2008 for ALL packages for Python 2.7, and so on.  I see from your later point that you build Python 2.7 with MSVC 2012.  That's a compelling point that we should make the compiler version explicit rather than implicit through python version.  I think it won't hurt us (we will probably build only the standard configuration), but it will help you.  Our recipes will only ever have features like: 

        - vc9  [win and py27]
        - vc10  [win and py34]
        - vc14  [win and py35]

but that should not preclude you from setting different features in your personal recipes.  The thing I don't know would be how you would force installation of your vc11-built Python in the first place, such that only those featured packages would get installed.

> Which pinning issues?

Right now, a package can simply depend on msvc_runtime, and the feature stuff should get it the right version.  If we depend on versions instead, then we need to add sections like:

requirements:
    run:
        - msvc_runtime  9.*  [win and py27]
        - msvc_runtime  10.*  [win and py34]
        - msvc_runtime  14.*  [win and py35]

Or else, I think your earlier point about version matching getting mixed up with feature matching remains an open issue, and essentially all installations with try to install the latest version of msvc_runtime, rather than the correct one for the given platform.

> True, but we needed a Python 2.7 that tracks vc11 because vc9 is too old to compile our C++ packages, and we cannot yet switch to Python 3.

This is a really hard problem.  I think you've found a good solution to it, but that's not really one that we can support.  In the name of compatibility, we need to stick with the mainstream version.  I feel your pain, though, and I hope we can find a way to at least not conflict with what you're trying to do.  FWIW, the Kitware folks often build and link Python and libraries statically in this situation: http://www.kitware.com/blog/home/post/742

> The recipes linked above already contain a full implementation of a (preliminary) variant of the jinja2 stuff for Windows.

Thanks.  These will be tremendously helpful.  Unfortunately, the problem is not just updating recipes.  We also have to update our internal build system to populate package metadata from templates in very different ways.  It currently can only draw from static meta.yaml files, which is why adoption of jinja2 stuff internally has been slow.  This build system is totally separate from conda-build, but can use conda-build and conda-recipes.  For our next release, we will be working towards converting all of our recipes to conda recipes, and consolidating the build system.",{},,User,False
