6626,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-09 14:40:52+00:00,16557526,pysam-developers/pysam,70921,jmarshall,6598771,pysam-developers,170158649,238574654,"BAM files contain a text header containing the textual `@` headers present and a binary header with the basic details of the sequences mapped against.  If the text contains no `@SQ` headers (which is uncommon but valid nonetheless), `samtools view` and other tools will reconstruct basic `@SQ` headers with just `SN` and `LN` fields from the binary header.  (There's a bit more discussion of this in samtools/samtools#548.)

_GSM850906_brain-E14.5-1.bam_ has only two actual text headers: the `@HD` line and the `@PG` line.  The `@SQ` information is present only in the binary header, and has been reconstructed on the fly by whatever tool you used to print out the headers.

So the question here is whether the `AlignmentFile text()` method should learn to do this reconstruction.  (At present, it is `sam_hdr_write()` that does this reconstruction in HTSlib, which is slightly unfortunate.)",{},,User,False
6627,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-04 12:57:29+00:00,16557526,pysam-developers/pysam,3380503,blaiseli,6598771,pysam-developers,198688194,270364554,"I finally managed to use a parser correctly: One needs to provide an instance, and not the class:

    > gtf_fetcher = tabixfile.fetch(""MtDNA"", parser=pysam.ctabix.asGTF())
    > gtf = next(gtf_fetcher)
    > gtf.contig
    'MtDNA'

