> I have currently 24 commits not added to any pull request, waiting for final testing, and 10 commits waiting in the queue for finalizing. The most important open feature is the fix for ForeignKey filter (issue 43) from the end of October. It was relative easy but it is complicated to write tests
> 
> I'm reoganizing the majority of commits listed in the release draft. Sometimes is the order important for better testing, sometimes I want to do folow-up steps of one feature in a successive group of commits even though I developed them like multiplexed by othe features, sometimes I changed anything in the example model and tests must be updated. Once I found a bug much later that a test did not tested anything. I try to follow the standard that every commit in PR works as expected or a known bug is described in the commit message that will be fixed exactly in the next commit, if it is better to separate them
> 
> E.g. the SFDC API 32.0 caused a bug, because they added an incorrect ForeignKey that is not related to any model (undocumented and probably also unused). So I first demonstrated the bug by increasing the API, then I fixed inspectdb and finally I fixed also the guaranted validity of the exported Django model. (by automatic renaming such ForeignKey to TextField and writing a big comment behind it)
