7854,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-29 20:35:21+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,544718,ebenolson,11752110,Lasagne,123934940,167873210,"I don't think it even needs to be as complicated as dynamically updating during initialization. Just keep a list in `helpers.py` and when someone defines a custom layer they can write

    lasagne.layers.helper._accepted_kwargs.append('some_new_kwarg')

to silence the warning (I would actually make it an Exception so it's not too easy to ignore). It shouldn't be confusing at all if we include text to that effect in the warning.

Travis should make sure we update the whitelist as long as tests are being written exercising the new kwarg. How often will this really be needed anyway? I think batch normalization is the first layer to use something beyond `deterministic`?

> At any rate, deterministic should probably be an allowed keyword argument even if the network does not involve any indeterministic layers, so we can encourage the generic ""deterministic=True for testing"" pattern.

Yes, I think a simple check to protect against typos is useful, but we shouldn't go overboard trying to determine if what the user is doing is logical.",{},,User,False
