8123,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-03 13:29:45+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,19779552,mesmith75,13271048,ganga-devs,198335375,270114152,"I'm not sure the templates were ever there.

As the penultimate step in the release before the upload to PyPi we make the distribution with 
```python
python setup.py sdist
```
For the default this only takes the python source, so the file ending .template is being ignored (see here for the defaults: https://docs.python.org/2/distutils/sourcedist.html).

We can try generating a list of files to be included (probably anything in the workspace directory), or just rename the file.",{},,User,False
8124,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-18 05:18:23+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,1102021,rob-c,13271048,ganga-devs,119954094,165675617,"OK, so this was something that crept up in 6.1.14 right at the last minute.

I've no idea how/if/when the mechanism for dealing with the indexes was broken but it was badly broken by the time we got to testing for the release. (I went back through the history and I think I can reproduce the problems I was seeing before 6.1.13).

I think the intention of the current code is that:

1) Data stored in the *.idx contains a small amount of cache data, enough to populate the 'jobs' summary or equivalent.
This data is loaded and stored in the ._index_cache dictionary which is now behind the get/setNodeIndexCache methods. This should be loaded at startup and cleared when the job is fully-read in from data.

2) Data stored in the 'data' XML files contains everything stored in the schema and nothing else. This is read into the ._data dictionary which is controlled through the get/setNodeData methods.
At some point this is translated into the __dict__ of the class object. At the moment right after the XML has been read.

3) The same getter function is used everywhere. This means that the getter function is potentially looking in ._index_cache, ._data and .__dict__ to find the attribute to return for a GangaObject.
This just got confusing so has been simplified slightly in 6.1.14 but more could be done here.


My plan is to try and consolidate this as much as is sensible to reduce the complexity of the getter method which currently adds confusion when trying to access 3 different dictionaries from my experience.
I'm not sure what benefit storing data in ._data for future access has if this is going to be deprecated by objects in __dict__ so I think this should be lost at the XML layer. Which then makes me wonder could the XML be read more directly into the final object rather than taking several steps.

I'm thinking of adding some further caching of data which can be easily/quickly accessed on startup but I'll only look into this once the whole loading of objects becomes much simpler.

Following the flow of the objects from XML into a fully loaded job has become a bit less painful and whilst the loading of a job is now safer due to various checks/locks in the repository this is still an area that would only benefit from being streamlined in the future.",{},,User,False
8127,IssueCommentEvent,2016-05-26 06:02:39+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,13677368,drmarkwslater,13271048,ganga-devs,156728493,221785101,"So after some messing around (mostly my fault for not reading the stack trace properly), I've found the following:

1. There was an additional lock up caused by a `_getReadAccess` call in `__deepcopy__` that was catching both Tasks and split jobs. This was actually the lock up I saw originally so the coverage is now running quite quickly and over all the tests. I'll clean the PR and all should be well.
2. I can't just blindly remove the `_getWriteAccess` call in the GangaObject setter as this caused other tests to fail. I don't know why but this definitely means we need to look at this more closely!
3. The root cause of this `_getWriteAccess` problem is that the `has_loaded` function is now `synchronised` (as of 3 days ago from #497). This means that a lock is acquired even if no loading needs to be done, hence the deadlock.

So, I would propose to remove the `synchronised` decorator for the `has_loaded` method and revisit this stuff ASAP to do a proper clean up and fix. What say others?",{},,User,False
