Looks like when `$SUDO mv -f ""$TEMP_DIR/letsencrypt-auto.permission-clone"" ""$0""` happens, the file is no longer executable. This causes `./letsencrypt-auto --le-auto-phase2` to fail. 

Simple test:
```sh
touch letsencrypt-auto
sudo touch letsencrypt-auto.permission-clone
sudo cp letsencrypt-auto letsencrypt-auto.permission-clone
```
Results: `-rw-r--r--    1 root     root         44442 Dec 17 00:28 letsencrypt-auto.permission-clone`

Looks like when you `$SUDO cp ""$TEMP_DIR/letsencrypt-auto"" ""$TEMP_DIR/letsencrypt-auto.permission-clone""` in alpine it takes the source chmod and the destination chown which is not the same as on debian and others. Perhaps someone with deeper alpine knowledge can comment on this. Added a temporary workaround in the template file. This allows an expected return of the version, however the test error still persists. Possible this cp issue is being generated in python?


",{},,User,False
