9254,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-18 01:30:54+00:00,79083614,python-trio/trio,609896,njsmith,26335827,python-trio,351558289,414023026,"OK, so the issue is that MacOS is weird:

```
>>> import sys
>>> sys.platform
'darwin'
>>> import socket
>>> a, b = socket.socketpair()
>>> a.getpeername()
''
>>> b.close()
>>> a.getpeername()
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
OSError: [Errno 22] Invalid argument
```

This is sorta-documented in the getpeername(2) man page:

>      [EINVAL]           socket has been shut down.

This is pretty annoying... on MacOS apparently you can have a situation where you accept a connection, read data from it, everything works fine... except that it is literally impossible to find out who you are talking to, because the kernel knows that but threw away the information before it let you start seeing the data.

Oh well, it is what it is.

So I guess we... ignore EINVAL when checking the socket in `SocketStream.__init__`? On Linux the man page says EINVAL only happens if the ""addrlen is invalid"", which should never happen if Python's `getpeername` is correctly written, and indeed I didn't manage to get an EINVAL when playing around a bit – e.g. calling it on a non-existent fd gives `EBADF`, and on a non-socket fd gives `ENOTSOCK`.

Alternatively, I guess we could remove the connected check altogether? If you try to wrap a not-connected socket in `SocketStream` then you're going to get some explosions soon enough...",{},MEMBER,User,False
9255,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-17 14:01:40+00:00,79083614,python-trio/trio,19316042,theelous3,26335827,python-trio,321966442,389877142,"This is on asks' end, and a fix will be pushed this evening :)

@njsmith was correct. The base methods each create a Session. Currently the code relies on python to clean up the sockets, but evidently this may not be fast enough. Using the Session is the correct way to go anyway, and doesn't have this issue :D Thanks for the feedback guys.",{},NONE,User,False
